Delicious, well-seasoned chicken. Nice toothsome yucca fries too. Stick to these basics and you'll be happy. There's other stuff on the menu, but chicken and yucca is where it's at.  This is juicier and more flavorful than American-style fried chicken, but they seem to cook to order (or at least not keep lots of pre-cooked chicken around like US-origin chains), so it can take a while. If you're dining in, you get a little number-placard so you can sit while you wait. Since the normal wait can be 15-20 minutes (based on two visits), consider ordering ahead online.  Expect a wait for the food, and remember it's not Kentucky-colonel style chicken, and you'll be happy. And you'll be even happier when you notice how inexpensive it is compared to the competition.

This is the second time I have been to this location. The first time, they did not have any of the spring mix. Therefore I could not get the grilled chicken salad. The second time, the manager took my order and didn't even ask me if I wanted the grilled or fried chicken. I remembered while I was paying to make sure I ordered the right type of chicken. She automatically put in my order for fried.  Then when I told her I wanted grilled, she had to check.  Come to find out, they did not have any grilled chicken ready. It was going to take 20 min. I told them, I will come back. When I came back in 20 min, my food was ready. They told me that they did not have the sauce that goes with it, but they have limes that they could give me. They were out of the sauce. I want to know why this location is not fully prepared for their customers. The manager acts like she doesn't want to be there. No energy whatsoever. The grilled chicken is flavorful and I like it. The plantains were delicious. But the beans were soupy. Not enough beans. The consistency was way off. But the flavor was not that bad. I am going to try another location to see if I get a better result.

The food was okay, but if you're looking for Peruvian-style chicken and yuca (and corresponding portions), this place is not for you (the name might fool you, but the first restaurant opened in Guatemala). This place is more like a hispanic version of KFC or Popeyes with similar portions and sizing options. Also, people weren't really that friendly...I now see that there are other reviews citing potential racist hostility, and after my experience, I'm sad to say I agree. There are many countries south of the US with similar types of cuisine and it's sad that we all can't just enjoy the food without getting hung up on language or skin color. They also got our order wrong. I probably won't go back here.
